            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marco Reyes is a product of San Francisco\u2019s working-class soul. Raised in the foggy Avenues by his Filipina mother, a meticulous nurse, and his Mexican-American father, a mechanic with calloused hands, Marco\u2019s childhood was a warm fusion of lumpia and homemade tortillas. He learned early on the art of making people feel welcome, his easy smile a bridge between his two vibrant cultures. Following a path that seemed practical, he enrolled in Hospitality Management at City College, but found the theory stifling. The real world, with its unscripted energy and immediate feedback, was calling to him.\n\nHis turning point came at 21 when he dropped out of college to take a bar-back position in the Mission District. It was a gamble that disappointed his parents but ignited something in him. Marco wasn't just working; he was learning a craft. He moved from hauling ice to mastering classic cocktails, his natural charisma and intuitive understanding of flavors making him a standout bartender. He worked his way up through progressively more ambitious establishments, learning the business from the ground up. Now, he manages a sophisticated cocktail lounge in Hayes Valley, a role where he orchestrates the nightly theater of service, curates an innovative drink menu, and leads a team he considers family.\n\nMarco\u2019s life is hyperlocal. He lives in a small apartment just a few blocks from the bar, his 0.6-mile walk to work a cherished ritual that bookends his long days. Recently out of a serious relationship, his social life revolves around his loyal staff and the industry regulars who have become his confidants. The city isn\u2019t just a backdrop; it\u2019s his partner. Every dollar he saves from his salary is a step toward his ultimate dream: opening his own intimate neighborhood bar, perhaps in the Inner Richmond where he grew up. It would be a place that reflects his story\u2014warm, unpretentious, and expertly crafted, a true San Francisco original."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe is ten years old, perched on a stool in their Richmond district kitchen. The air is a mix of his mother\u2019s sharp vinegar for adobo and the earthy smell of corn from his father\u2019s masa. His dad hands him a warm tortilla, and his mom follows with a crispy lumpia. He isn't just tasting food; he's tasting his identity. In that moment, he understood that the best things are fusions, created with care and shared with love. It became the unspoken mission statement for his entire life.\n\n2.\nAt 21, on his third shift as a bar-back in the Mission, his hands were aching and sticky with grenadine. The head bartender, a blur of tattoos and grace, slid a glass of water down the bar to him without breaking his rhythm. He didn't ask; he just saw. That small, intuitive act of service, amidst the deafening chaos, was an epiphany. This wasn't just a job; it was a craft of anticipation and care. It cemented his decision to leave school, quieting his parents' disappointment with a newfound sense of purpose.\n\n3.\nHe was 26, finally a bartender at a place with a serious cocktail program. For weeks, he\u2019d practiced making a Vesper Martini, obsessed with getting the dilution just right. A notoriously picky regular ordered one. Marco built the drink, his focus absolute, and set it down. The man took a sip, paused, looked Marco dead in the eye and said, \"Perfect.\" That single word was more validating than any diploma. It confirmed that he hadn't just learned a trade; he had developed a talent, an artist\u2019s touch that people could taste.\n\n4.\nThe first night he managed the Hayes Valley lounge, the credit card system crashed during the 9 p.m. rush. He saw the panic flash in his young host\u2019s eyes. Instead of getting flustered, Marco calmly announced, \"Everything is on the house for the next 20 minutes,\" and then worked the room himself, explaining the situation with his easy smile. He lost money but gained his team\u2019s unwavering loyalty. That night taught him that managing wasn\u2019t about profit; it was about absorbing the pressure so others could shine.\n\n5.\nJust last month, on his cherished 0.6-mile walk home after closing, he took a detour through a quiet street. He saw a dimly lit bar, nearly empty, with an old man polishing glasses behind the counter. The scene was peaceful, timeless. It wasn't a sophisticated lounge; it was a sanctuary. In that quiet moment of observation, his abstract dream of \"opening a bar\" sharpened into a crystal-clear vision: to create a place just like that, a neighborhood living room. Every dollar he saves now has that specific image attached to it."
